Exercise 1: Understanding Data Visualization

Why data visualization is important in data analysis

Data visualization is important because it transforms raw data into graphical formats (charts, graphs, plots), making it easier to understand patterns, trends, and outliers.

Key benefits:

* Helps identify trends quickly (e.g., increase or decrease over time)
* Makes complex datasets easier to interpret
* Supports better decision-making
* Reveals relationships between variables
* Improves communication of insights to non-technical audiences

⸻

Purpose of a line graph

A line graph is used to show how data changes over time or in a continuous sequence.

It is mainly used to:

* Track trends (growth, decline, fluctuations)
* Compare changes across time intervals
* Visualize continuous data (like temperature, stock prices, etc.)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Temperature data for a week
temperatures = [72, 74, 76, 80, 82, 78, 75]

# Days of the week
days = ["Mon", "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri", "Sat", "Sun"]

# Create line plot
plt.plot(days, temperatures, marker='o')

# Labels and title
plt.xlabel("Day")
plt.ylabel("Temperature (°F)")
plt.title("Weekly Temperature Variation")

# Display plot
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Monthly sales data
sales = [5000, 5500, 6200, 7000, 7500]

# Months
months = ["Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May"]

# Create bar chart
plt.bar(months, sales)

# Labels and title
plt.xlabel("Month")
plt.ylabel("Sales Amount ($)")
plt.title("Monthly Sales Overview")

# Display plot
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv("/content/Student Mental health.csv")

# Histogram of CGPA
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
sns.histplot(data=df, x="What is your CGPA?", color="skyblue", bins=10)

plt.title("Distribution of Students' CGPA")
plt.xlabel("CGPA")
plt.ylabel("Count")

plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Charger le jeu de données avec le bon nom de fichier
path = '/content/Student Mental health.csv'
df = pd.read_csv(path)

# Afficher les 5 premières lignes
display(df.head())

# Visualisation de l'anxiété par genre
plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))

sns.countplot(
    data=df,
    x="Choose your gender",
    hue="Do you have Anxiety?",
    palette="Set2"
)

plt.title("Anxiety Levels Across Genders")
plt.xlabel("Gender")
plt.ylabel("Number of Students")

plt.show()


import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Correction du chemin du fichier
df = pd.read_csv("/content/Student Mental health.csv")

# Conversion en numérique (nom exact de la colonne : 'Do you have Panic attack?')
df["panic_numeric"] = df["Do you have Panic attack?"].map({"Yes": 1, "No": 0})

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))

sns.scatterplot(
    data=df,
    x="Age",
    y="panic_numeric",
    hue="Do you have Panic attack?",
    palette="coolwarm",
    s=80
)

plt.title("Relationship Between Age and Panic Attacks")
plt.xlabel("Age")
plt.ylabel("Panic Attacks (0 = No, 1 = Yes)")

plt.yticks([0, 1])

plt.show()
